The \emph{toric ideal of a matroid} $M$, denoted by $I_M$, is the kernel of the map $\varphi_M$.

Neil White made three conjectures of growing difficulty that describe generators of the ideal $I_M$.

\begin{conjecture}[White 1980, \cite{Wh80}]\label{ConjectureWeakWhite}
The toric ideal of a matroid is generated in degree $2$.
\end{conjecture}

The family $\mathfrak{B}$ of bases of $M$ satisfies \emph{symmetric exchange property} (the reader is referred to \cite{Ox92} for background of matroid theory, and to \cite{La15} for other exchange properties). That is, for every bases $B_1,B_2$ and $e\in B_1\setminus B_2$ there exists $f\in B_2\setminus B_1$, such that both sets $B_1'=(B_1\setminus e)\cup f$ and $B_2'=(B_2\setminus f)\cup e$ are bases. In this case we say that the quadratic binomial $y_{B_1}y_{B_2}-y_{B_1'}y_{B_2'}$ \emph{corresponds to symmetric exchange}. It is clear that such binomials belong to the ideal $I_M$. 

\begin{conjecture}[White 1980, \cite{Wh80}]\label{ConjectureClassicWhite}
The toric ideal of a matroid is generated by quadratic binomials corresponding to symmetric exchanges. 
\end{conjecture}

The third and the strongest among White's conjectures describing generators of the ideal $I_M$ turned out to be equivalent to Conjecture \ref{ConjectureClassicWhite} (see the discussion in Section $4$ of \cite{LaMi14}). 

The original conjectures due to White were expressed in the combinatorial language. Conjecture \ref{ConjectureWeakWhite} asserts that if two multisets of bases of a matroid have equal union (as a multiset), then one can pass between them by a sequence of steps, in each step exchanging two bases for another two bases of the same union (as a multiset). In Conjecture \ref{ConjectureClassicWhite} additionally each step corresponds to a symmetric exchange. Therefore White's conjectures do not depend on the field ${\mathbb{{K}}}$.

Conjectures \ref{ConjectureWeakWhite} and \ref{ConjectureClassicWhite} are known to be true for many special classes of matroids: graphic matroids \cite{Bl08}, strongly base orderable matroids \cite{LaMi14} (so also for transversal matroids), sparse paving matroids \cite{Bo13}, and for matroids of rank at most $3$ \cite{Ka10} (see also other related papers \cite{Co07,HeHi02,Sc11}).

The first result valid for arbitrary matroids was the confirmation of White's conjecture up to saturation. Let $J_M$ be the ideal generated by quadratic binomials corresponding to symmetric exchanges. Clearly, $J_M\subset I_M$ and Conjecture \ref{ConjectureClassicWhite} asserts that the ideals $J_M$ and $I_M$ are equal. Recall that two homogeneous ideals are equal up saturation with respect to the ideal generated by all variables if and only if they are equal starting from some degree. 

\begin{theorem}[Laso{\'n}, Micha{\l}ek, \cite{LaMi14}]\label{TheoremLasonMichalek}
The toric ideal of a matroid and the ideal generated by quadratic binomials corresponding to symmetric exchanges are equal starting from some degree. 
\end{theorem}

Here we prove another result towards White's conjecture which is valid for arbitrary matroids. 

Consider a single matroid $M$, then by Hilbert's basis theorem the ideal $I_M$ is finitely generated. In particular it is generated in some degree, however so far we did not have any effective bound. If we fix the size of the ground set, then there are only finitely many matroids on it. Hence in this case there is a common bound on degree in which the corresponding toric ideals are generated. But, when we fix only the rank, then the number of matroids of that rank is infinite. We prove that in this case there is also a common bound on degree in which the corresponding toric ideals are generated. Our bound is explicit.

\begin{theorem}\label{TheoremMain}
The toric ideal associated to a matroid of rank $r$ is generated in degree at most $(r+3)!$.  
\end{theorem}

In the combinatorial language the meaning of Theorems \ref{TheoremLasonMichalek} and \ref{TheoremMain} is the following. Let $M$ be a matroid of rank $r$. Let $\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}$ be two multisets of $k$ bases of $M$ with equal union (as a multiset). Theorem \ref{TheoremLasonMichalek} asserts that if $k\geq f(M)$ (for some function $f$), then one can pass between $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ by a sequence of steps, in each step exchanging two bases for two bases created by a symmetric exchange. While Theorem \ref{TheoremLasonMichalek} asserts that if $k\geq(r+3)!$, then one can pass between $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ by a sequence of steps, in each step exchanging $(r+3)!$ bases for another $(r+3)!$ bases of the same union (as a multiset). Thus in Theorem \ref{TheoremMain} the steps between multisets of bases are less precise (consist of exchanging $(r+3)!$ instead of $2$ bases), but the lower bound on $k$ (the size of multisets of bases) is better ($(r+3)!$ instead of $f(M)$).

\begin{corollary}\label{CorollaryDecidable}
Checking if Conjecture \ref{ConjectureClassicWhite} is true for matroids of a fixed rank is a decidable problem (it is enough to check connectivity of a finite number of graphs).
\end{corollary}

Equality of saturations of the ideals $J_M$ and $I_M$ from Theorem \ref{TheoremLasonMichalek} implies equality of their radicals. Since the ideal $I_M$ is prime, it is also radical. Thus the radical of $J_M$ equals to $I_M$. In other words, for every element $a$ of the toric ideal of a matroid there exists a power $n$, such that $a^n$ is generated by quadratic binomials corresponding to symmetric exchanges. We can make this statement more explicit. 

\begin{corollary}\label{CorollaryRadical}
Suppose the characteristic of the field ${\mathbb{{K}}}$ is $2$. Then for every matroid of rank $r$, the $2r(r+3)!$-th power of every element of its toric ideal is generated by quadratic binomials corresponding to symmetric exchanges.  
\end{corollary}


\section{Preliminaries}


Blasiak \cite{Bl08} proposed a very nice and simple translation of the problem of generating the ideal $I_M$ to the problem of connectivity of some graphs naturally constructed from matroids. We are going to use this approach.

Suppose $M$ is a matroid whose ground set can be partitioned into $k$ (for $k\geq 3$) disjoint bases (so the ground set is of size $r(E)k$). We call such a matroid a \emph{$k$-matroid}, and define for it a \emph{$k$-base graph} denoted by $\mathfrak{B}_k(M)$. Vertices of $\mathfrak{B}_k(M)$ correspond to sets of $k$ pairwise disjoint bases of $M$ (partitions into bases of the ground set). An edge joins vertices with nonempty intersection. That is, sets of bases $\{B_1,\dots,B_k\}$ and $\{B_1',\dots,B_k'\}$ are connected if for some $i,j$ equality $B_i=B_j'$ holds. A simple corollary of the proof of Proposition $2.1$ from \cite{Bl08} gives the following.

\begin{proposition}[Blasiak, \cite{Bl08}]\label{PropositionBlasiakReduction}
Let $\mathfrak{C}$ be a class of matroids that is closed under deletions (that do not lower the rank of a matroid) and adding parallel elements. Suppose that for every $k>n$ and for every $k$-matroid $M$ in $\mathfrak{C}$ the $k$-base graph $\mathfrak{B}_k(M)$ is connected. Then for every matroid $M$ in $\mathfrak{C}$, the toric ideal $I_M$ is generated in degree at most $n$.
\end{proposition}

In particular, in order to prove Conjecture \ref{ConjectureWeakWhite} it is enough to show that for every $k>2$ and for every $k$-matroid $M$ the $k$-base graph $\mathfrak{B}_k(M)$ is connected.


